  "record": {
    "abstract": "We present a study of the inclusive charged-particle transverse momentum ($p_{\\rm T}$) spectra as a function of charged-particle multiplicity density at mid-pseudorapidity, ${\\rm d}N_{\\rm ch}/{\\rm d}\\eta$, in pp collisions at $\\sqrt{s}$ = 5.02 and 13 TeV covering the kinematic range $|\\eta|<0.8$ and $0.15<p_{\\rm{T}}<20$ GeV/$c$. The results are presented for events with at least one charged particle in $|\\eta|<1$ (INEL$ >0$). The $p_{\\rm T}$ spectra are reported for two multiplicity estimators covering different pseudorapidity regions. The $p_{\\rm T}$ spectra normalized to that for INEL $>0$ show little energy dependence. Moreover, the high-$p_{\\rm T}$ yields of charged particles increase faster than the charged-particle multiplicity density. The average $\\it{p}_{\\rm T}$ as a function of multiplicity and transverse spherocity is reported for pp collisions at $\\sqrt{s}=13$ TeV. For low- (high-) spherocity events, corresponding to jet-like (isotropic) events, the average $p_{\\rm T}$ is higher (smaller) than that measured in INEL $>0$ pp collisions. Within uncertainties, the functional form of $\\langle p_{\\rm T} \\rangle(N_{\\rm ch})$ is not affected by the spherocity selection. While EPOS LHC gives a good description of many features of data, PYTHIA overestimates the average $p_{\\rm T}$ in jet-like events.",
    "access_urls": {
